\description{
Top-level entry point for the multivariate site--trait model of
Nakagawa et al. (in prep) functional biogeography (and the related
behavioural-syndromes / phylogenetic / systematic-mapping reduced-rank
models). Long-format input with one row per (unit, trait)
observation; glmmTMB-style formula syntax for fixed effects, plus
a 3 x 5 grid of covariance-structure keywords organised by
\emph{correlation} (none / phylo / spatial) and \emph{mode}
(scalar / unique / indep / dep / latent):
}
\details{
\tabular{llllll}{
\strong{correlation \\ mode} \tab \strong{scalar} \tab \strong{unique} \tab \strong{indep} \tab \strong{dep} \tab \strong{latent} \cr
\emph{none}    \tab (omit)             \tab \code{\link[=unique]{unique()}}         \tab \code{\link[=indep]{indep()}}         \tab \code{\link[=dep]{dep()}}         \tab \code{\link[=latent]{latent()}}         \cr
\emph{phylo}   \tab \code{\link[=phylo_scalar]{phylo_scalar()}}   \tab \code{\link[=phylo_unique]{phylo_unique()}}   \tab \code{\link[=phylo_indep]{phylo_indep()}}   \tab \code{\link[=phylo_dep]{phylo_dep()}}   \tab \code{\link[=phylo_latent]{phylo_latent()}}   \cr
\emph{spatial} \tab \code{\link[=spatial_scalar]{spatial_scalar()}} \tab \code{\link[=spatial_unique]{spatial_unique()}} \tab \code{\link[=spatial_indep]{spatial_indep()}} \tab \code{\link[=spatial_dep]{spatial_dep()}} \tab \code{\link[=spatial_latent]{spatial_latent()}} \cr
}

The four "quartet" modes (\code{unique} / \code{indep} / \code{dep} / \code{latent})
encode covstruct intent under a strict always-paired-vs-always-alone
convention:
\itemize{
\item \code{latent + unique} (paired) — the \strong{decomposition} mode:
\eqn{\boldsymbol\Sigma = \boldsymbol\Lambda \boldsymbol\Lambda^\top + \boldsymbol\Psi}.
\code{unique} standalone is also legitimate (e.g. observation-level
random effects), but the canonical pattern is paired with \code{latent}.
\item \code{indep} (alone) — the \strong{marginal-only} mode: each trait gets its
own variance, no cross-trait covariance.
\item \code{dep} (alone) — the \strong{full unstructured} mode: \eqn{\boldsymbol\Sigma}
is free with \eqn{T(T+1)/2} parameters via a Cholesky factor.
}

Plus the supporting \code{\link[=phylo_slope]{phylo_slope()}} (random slope), \code{\link[=meta_known_V]{meta_known_V()}}
(known-V meta-analytic), and the engine-internal \code{propto()} /
\code{equalto()} covstructs (used by the canonical keywords above; not
typically called directly). See \code{vignette("api-keyword-grid")} for a
one-paragraph tour of each cell.

\code{gllvmTMB()} parses the glmmTMB-style formula, checks the long-format
data, and dispatches to the underlying TMB template (built on sdmTMB's
SPDE machinery). Covariance-structure terms (\code{latent()}, \code{unique()},
\code{propto()}, \code{equalto()}, \code{spatial()}) are processed by extending the
formula parser and the TMB template.

Per the manuscript, when stacking traits one should set
\code{dispformula = ~ 0} so that no implicit residual variance competes
with structured \verb{unique(0 + trait | …)} terms. \code{gllvmTMB()} enforces
this internally.

\strong{Multi-trial binomial}. The TMB engine evaluates \code{dbinom(y, n_trials, p)}
so binomial fits are not restricted to Bernoulli (size = 1). To pass a
per-row trial count, use either:
\itemize{
\item \code{cbind(successes, failures) ~ ...} on the LHS of the formula
(canonical R / \code{glmmTMB} convention; recommended), or
\item a flat response \code{y} with \code{weights = n_trials} (the alternative
glmmTMB API).
}
Both interfaces produce identical fits. For Bernoulli data, omit
\code{weights} and use a 0/1 response; the engine sets \code{n_trials = 1} and
the likelihood is identical to the previous Bernoulli-only behaviour.

\strong{Delta (hurdle) families.} \code{delta_lognormal()} and \code{delta_gamma()}
use a \emph{single} linear predictor for both components: presence is
\eqn{\Pr(y > 0) = \mathrm{invlogit}(\eta)} and the positive-component
mean is \eqn{E[y \mid y > 0] = \exp(\eta)}. This matches sdmTMB's
standard delta default (one fixed-effects matrix, one set of trait
random effects). The shared-predictor scheme is the simplest hurdle
formulation; a future release may decouple the two predictors so
presence and abundance can have independent fixed and random effects.
Only \code{type = "standard"} (the default) is currently wired in the
multivariate engine; \code{type = "poisson-link"} is on the roadmap. Each
delta family carries one per-trait dispersion of the \emph{positive}
component (no extra Bernoulli dispersion). The response must be
non-negative.
\subsection{Per-trait residual variance: when does it activate?}{

"Residual" in a mixed-effects model is \strong{scale-relative}: what
counts as residual variance shifts as you add levels to the model.
In a no-\code{unique} Gaussian fit, the residual is row-level noise
captured by a single shared \code{sigma_eps}. Once you add a per-row
\code{unique(0 + trait | obs)} term, the \emph{row-level} residual is now T
per-trait random-effect variances and \code{sigma_eps} is auto-suppressed
to avoid double-counting. Once you also add \code{unique(0 + trait | site)}
on top, the row-level term remains the residual and the \code{site}-level
term is now an additional, \emph{higher-level} random effect — not a
residual at all. The dispatch table below records this explicitly
for the configurations the engine supports today.

For continuous-family responses (Gaussian, lognormal, Gamma) the
engine has one residual scale parameter, \code{sigma_eps}. By default
\code{sigma_eps} is \strong{estimated as a single shared scalar across all
continuous-family rows} — per-trait residual variances only appear
if you explicitly add a per-row \code{unique(...)} (or, when Phase B
lands, \code{indep(...)}) term. The dispatch is automatic:

\describe{
\item{No \code{unique} / \code{indep}, continuous families present}{One
shared \code{sigma_eps} across all rows. \emph{Not} per-trait.}
\item{No \code{unique} / \code{indep}, no continuous families}{\code{sigma_eps}
is mapped off; the family's intrinsic dispersion handles the
residual.}
\item{\code{unique(0 + trait | g)} where \code{g} has fewer levels than
rows (e.g. \code{g = "site"})}{\code{sigma_eps} is still estimated as the
row-level residual; the \code{unique} term adds a per-trait random
effect at level \code{g} on top.}
\item{\code{unique(0 + trait | obs)} at the per-row level (one
level per row), continuous families fitted}{\code{sigma_eps} is
auto-suppressed (mapped off, fixed at a tiny stabiliser); the
T per-trait \code{unique} random effects \emph{are} the residual. A
one-shot \code{cli::cli_inform} fires at fit time announcing the
auto-suppression.}
\item{\code{unique(0 + trait | obs)} at the per-row level,
non-Gaussian or mixed-family fit}{Treated as observation-level
random effects (OLRE). For Bernoulli traits the OLRE is
statistically unidentifiable and is mapped off; for hurdle /
delta families a warning is emitted (see "Per-family-aware OLRE
selection" below).}
\item{\code{indep(0 + trait | obs)} at the per-row level (Phase B,
not yet implemented)}{Mathematically equivalent to the per-row
\code{unique} case; same auto-suppression dispatch.}
}

Mnemonic: continuous-family \code{sigma_eps} is the default; per-row
\code{unique} / \code{indep} replaces it with T per-trait residuals; non-per-row
\code{unique} / \code{indep} adds a higher-level random effect on top of
\code{sigma_eps}; non-continuous families never carry \code{sigma_eps}
regardless.

\strong{Per-family-aware OLRE selection.} When \verb{unique(0 + trait | <unit_obs>)}
is at per-row resolution (i.e. one row per \verb{(trait, unit_obs)} cell),
the resulting per-trait random effects on the linear predictor are an
observation-level random effect (OLRE). The engine now decides per
trait what to do with the OLRE variance based on the trait's response
family:
\itemize{
\item \strong{single-trial Bernoulli} (\code{binomial()}, all rows have
\code{n_trials == 1}): \code{theta_diag_W[t]} and the corresponding
\code{s_W} column are mapped off. The OLRE is statistically
unidentifiable here (no within-cell replication) and the MLE
is the trivial boundary \eqn{\sigma_W \to 0}; pinning the
parameter at \eqn{\sigma_W \approx 10^{-6}} removes the
spurious free parameter and emits a one-shot informational
message. Multi-trial binomial (via \code{cbind(succ, fail)} or
\code{weights = n_trials}) is identifiable and fit normally.
\item \strong{delta / hurdle families} (\code{delta_lognormal()},
\code{delta_gamma()}): OLRE is fit as before, but a one-shot
warning is emitted because the OLRE acts on the \emph{shared}
linear predictor of the hurdle and mixes presence and
positive-component noise.
\item \strong{all other families}: OLRE is fit as before.
}
In a mixed-family fit (per-row family list) the per-trait decision
applies only to the affected trait. References: Nakagawa &
Schielzeth (2010) \emph{Biol. Rev.} 85: 935-956; Nakagawa, Johnson &
Schielzeth (2017) \emph{J. R. Soc. Interface} 14: 20170213.
}
}
